 that protects both city and mire from predatory terms.\",\n        \"Return the relic-needle to the Order under conditions that respect Willowwife rites.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Ossa Wreath\", \"lines\": \"You walked our reeds once and left a breath of your name on them, Kezra, and the stems still lean when you pass as if listening for the rest. The queen’s memory tastes the air when the lanterns go out, and she is patient the way peat is patient, turning years into fuel unless someone remembers the first fire was a promise. Bring the needle back from its wet hiding and do not let the Order pound its return into a sermon that taxes us until we must lie to eat. Bargain with a name that costs you without breaking you, because payment that ruins the payer is just another story the reeds tell about city-folk who drown standing up. If you must write, write like a pilot setting poles under everyone’s feet at once, and if you must bleed a word, make it one you can live with when the moths come home in Fogfast and the children ask why the water sings their names at night.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"The Drowned Queen's Memory\", \"lines\": \"I am not a demon, little oath-binder, though the Order’s lances would be happier if I wore horns you could polish and hang. I am the meal the river keeps eating and serving again, the taste of vows washed thin until they break into brine, the patience of weeds that grow through your stone and call it mercy when they hold you up. Names are salt and songs together, and I am hungry, because every dry season your measures weigh us and call it fairness and every flood year your bridges call it fate. Do not bring me the name you wear in markets and halls, the one that buys respect like soap; bring me the name you tasted in your mouth when you were lost and no one was listening, the one that wicks tears into strength. Feed me such a name with the needle’s point laid on still water, and I will let the children find the long way home without losing their shadows, and I will let pilots who whistle wrong live long enough to learn the right tune, and I will remember that mercy is a kind of geometry that can be mapped if the map is brave.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Prior Ansel Thornward\", \"lines\": \"We do not traffic lightly with river masks or sorrowed memories, for the city’s vows were cut to spare the living an unending negotiation with what drowns and what whispers. And yet, I have seen the Exchange tally grief into ledgers and the Hall of Shares price absolution by the ell, and I will not pretend the Keep’s rain-chains sing only hymns I approve. Bring back the relic, yes, and if you must bargain then bind the bargain to your own breath and bones so that no innocent pays a tithe you agreed without their hearing. We will witness, because light shies from unobserved vows, and we will insist that the needle’s return be received under Willowwife rites, because a debt returned with scorn is not settled, it is salted. Mind this too, Kezra Thorneglass: oaths are scaffolds, not cages, and if you build this Accord like a scaffold, I will help stand watch against the ones who climb it to take aim at the reed-women who kept us in silk when the moths were dying.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Kezra Thorneglass\", \"lines\": \"I have a name I have never written, a name kept for nights when the water in my bowl shows me a sky full of futures I will not buy, and when I speak it even the thorn under my tongue pricks like a memory of winter. I will feed that name to you on a still surface with the relic’s point resting like a compass needle, and I will not flinch, because fear is a poor scribe and bargains written in fear blur when the ink dries. In return, we will set terms that refrain from drowning anyone slowly with clever measures, a passage kept by tokens woven in bone-white reeds and renewed by the first moths of Fogfast, so that safe ways are not hoarded as secrets but tended as common vows. Ossa, I will write the Accord like it is a raft we all must stand on at once, ward and mire together, and I will argue it until the Hall stops playing at famine and the Order stops pretending that hunger is a test of faith we should all pass. Prior, I will let you witness and strike your thorn on my tongue if I shade a truth, and I will return the needle under rites that taste of peat and river smoke, because a relic that forgets its making will only remember how to hurt.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Breathe the True Name\", \"text\": \"Kezra sets a dark bowl on the spear-straight water where it touches the old channel, rings the lip with a trembling line of salt, and lowers the relic-needle so its reflection becomes a second, downward-pointing thorn. The hush-silk is wrapped at the throat and the mnemonic lantern is turned down to a low memory, and in that held quiet Kezra speaks the breath-name that only the reeds and the empty midnight heard before. It tastes of peat smoke and childhood fear and the clean ache after a rescue, and the thorn under the tongue pierces as if it has found the first vow again. Ossa hums a Willowwife cradle-tone and Prior Ansel pricks his own tongue in solidarity, and the ghost lights gather like witnesses rather than bait. The queen’s memory listens without moving the water, and the straight-cut channel softens at the edges, and when the name is finished the bowl’s reflection lifts as if it wants to be kept forever but accepts instead the promise of return. \", \"outcome\": \"The Drowned Queen’s Memory accepts the true name and takes only a sliver of its salt, and shadows step back to their owners like dogs called in from the yard at dusk. She yields a token woven of bone-white reeds and sealed with a wet imprint of the needle’s tip, declaring that those who carry it will be shown the slower, safer curves of the Mire without paying with light or laughter. The Accord is written in firm strokes and witnessed by Willowwives and Order alike, setting passages by season, forbidding predatory tariffs, and naming a public lantern at the Weir Market whose pattern grants access without guild toll. Kezra feels lighter and a little hollow, and for a season their reflection lags a heartbeat behind and their shadow is thin at noon, but the cost is theirs and harms no other; the Willowwives call it honorable hunger. The relic-needle is returned to the Order in Ossa’s hands under peat-smoke and thistle prayers, strengthening trust between chapel and mire; in the weeks that follow the moth-frames thrive, pilots speak of lights that warn instead of lure, and the Night Cartographers quietly raise their prices on secret routes they can no longer claim are the only safe ways.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C2\", \"title\": \"Name the City’s Founding Vow\", \"text\": \"Kezra kneels with the relic-needle on the Oathstone rub carried from the Lantern Archive, and recites the first, rough-cut vow that raised the palisade against flood and famine. The drowned queen’s memory is invited to taste that vow through the water, and to bind her hunger not to one person but to the city’s promise when it remembers itself and to the lanterns that remember what water tries to erase. Prior Ansel lends the Order’s breath to the recitation, and Ossa threads a Willowwife reed through the knot so that the compact’s weight sits where river and stone meet, not where coin and ledger argue. Kezra keeps personal names sheathed and instead offers stewardship in the open, a schedule of rites at Fogfast and Uncasked Evening, and a ledger of reparations to be paid in work and seed rather than in bare coin. The ghost lights sway like a congregation in a steady wind, and the straight waterway waits like an unstruck bell for the queen’s answer. \", \"outcome\": \"The queen accepts a lesser tasting of the city’s founding vow and agrees to grant safe passage to those who carry a reed token stamped 